### Provide a Basic Summary of the Data Set Using Python, Numpy and/or Pandas[¶](#Provide-a-Basic-Summary-of-the-Data-Set-Using-Python,-Numpy-and/or-Pandas)

Here the statistics of the data:

*   Training data: it is the dataset that will be used to train the neural network with backpropagation following the "direction" to minimize the cross entropy. Total number of images in the training dataset: 34799
*   Validation data: it is the dataset that will be used to validate the neural network until the expected accuracy is reached. Total number of images in the validation dataset: 4410
*   Testing data: it is the dataset that will be used for the final test of the neural network, only when the tuning will be completed. Total number of images in the testing dataset: 12630

All images are 32x32 pixels and in rgb (3 color channels).

## Step 2: Design and Test a Model Architecture[¶](#Step-2:-Design-and-Test-a-Model-Architecture)

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

### Pre-process the Data Set (normalization, grayscale, etc.)[¶](#Pre-process-the-Data-Set-(normalization,-grayscale,-etc.))

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

As pre-processing technique, the histogram equalization was chosen. The original technique provided by opencv2 [Histogram Equalization](https://docs.opencv.org/4.1.2/d4/d1b/tutorial_histogram_equalization.html "Histogram Equalization") was however designed for gray images.

Therefore the technique was adapted for a color image, by converting the image to the HLS space and equalizing the histogram of the L channel which is the luminosity.

This way the images will be equalized in terms of luminosity, which means that the histogram of the luminosity will be uniform and not biased to a certain luminosity (e.g. if the image is very bright or very dark). Instead the other two channels were not touched.

As final step, the equalized image was converted to gray-scale.

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

From the analysis of the training data, it was seen that the distribution of images per class is not uniform.

Many classes have just a few sample images (e.g. 200), instead for some classes there are a lot of images (2000). This can affect the learning of the neural network.

Therefore in the next step the training data is augmented, by creating new data from the classes which have a few images (<1000), in order to have for all classes a number of data roughly between 1000 and 2000.

The new images are created from the original training images by applying a random rotation betwen -15 and 15 degrees, so that the data with variation can help the training process and avoid overfitting.

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

Here we see now how the training data which have been augmented are spread with more uniform distribution among all the classes (roughly between 1000 and 2000).

</div>

### Model Architecture[¶](#Model-Architecture)

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

The original LeNet5 architecture was adapted just with the following changes:

*   A dropout technique was applied to the output of the last fully convolutional layer
*   The 1D output convolutional layer has to have size equal to the number of classes we want to classify i.e. the number of different traffic signs (43)

Therefore the architecture consists of the following layers:

*   1st convolutional layer + relu activation + pooling -> output is 14x14x6
*   2nd convolution layer + relu activation + pooling -> output is 5x5x16
*   Flattening -> output is 400
*   1st fully connected layer + relu activation -> output is 120
*   2nd fully connected layer + relu activation + dropout -> output is 84
*   Last fully connected layer -> output is 43 classes

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

### Train, Validate and Test the Model[¶](#Train,-Validate-and-Test-the-Model)

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

The following hyperparameters were manually iteratively tuned to obtain the desired accuracy on the validation set (> 0.93):

*   Number of epochs was set to 50
*   Batch size was set to 64: reducing it from the initial value of 128 helped a lot to obtain the desired performance!
*   Learning rate was set to 0.0003
*   Keep probability in the training phase for dropout on the first fully convolution layer was set to 0.5 (in validation and test it was set back to 1.0 in order to have all activations available)

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

Obtained accuracies:

*   On training data: 99.8%
*   On validation data: 94.6%

</div>

</div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

After the parameters were satisfactory, the same classifier was run on the test data, for which a slightly lower accuracy was obtained: 91.4%

This was a little surprising because also the accuracy on the validation data is pretty high. Therefore the reason could be that the validation data is very similar to the training data, while the testing data have some differences.

</div>

</div>

</div>

## Conclusions[¶](#Conclusions)

All in all, the classifier is able to meet the specifications i.e. accuracy higher than 0.93% on the validation data.

In this project, a fair amount of time was spent to improve the data with reprocessing and augmentation, which is for sure a pre-condition for the classifier to be trained on "good" data.

On the other hand, lot of time was spent to manually tune the parameters (epochs, batch size, learning rate and small adaptations of the LeNet architecture including dropouts). As an improvement, this process could be automatized in order to find the best combination of parameters quickly avoiding manual tuning.

Lastly, it was observed a lower accuracy on the testing data compared to the validation. This could mean that the training and validation data tend to be similar, while the testing data are different. Therefore, to obtain better performances, more analysis could be done on the data, also trying different splits between training, validation and testing. This could also improve the result on the new test images.

</div>
